</table></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=larraquemeleagrance>Larraque Meleagrance</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Radical Dreamer</span><br>  Posts: 1343<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(5/23/03 9:57 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1588.topic&index=16>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Most bestest fantabulistic video game(s) ever?</span><hr size=1> Pool of Radiance - You never forget your first RPG love. I loved the whole gold box series (all 9 games) but this is the one I hold in highest regard. Curse of the Azure bonds a close second. <br>
<br>
Ancient Art of War - The first real time strategy game I ever played, back on an 8086. The graphics nowadays are extremely dated, but the game is STILL a classic. <br>
<br>
Planescape Torment - One of the greatest story achievements in PC gaming history. It's more an interactive novel than a PC game. Baldur's Gate series is good, as is Icewind Dale, but when the Infinity Engine is finally put to rest, this is the one I'm going to remember the most fondly. <br>
<br>
Pokemon games - Sure, there's 20 different ones now, and each and every one is exactly the same, and it's licensed to hell into a million different formats, and it seems very very kiddy, but the game is FUN and addictive. There's a lot of appeal to them. If you're a fan of roleplaying or strategy games and you've never tried them, you're missing out on a lot. <br>
<br>
Heroes of Might and Magic 3 Complete - One of the greatest, most addictive games I've ever played. I was almost afraid to load it up on saturday mornings because often times it would be saturday evening before I stopped playing! Heroes 4 was a huge step backwards for the series, but #3 was a lot of fun. Definately worth the price of admission, and this game will still be very fun, addictive and playable ten years from now. A true classic.<br>
<br>
Super Smash Bros Melee - The greatest, craziest, four player fighting game you'll ever play. Pikachu just kicked your ass out of pokemon stadium, bitch! <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Halo - *hugs Halo tight*<br>
<br>
Mechassault - Single player is ok. But this game is a blast on XBox live. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Chrono Cross - The best japanese final fantasy style video game I've ever played. Good story. <br>
<br>
Xenosaga Episode 1 - Der Wille Sur Macht (The WIll to Power) - For the past two months, I have been playing this outstanding PS2 exclusive. And Episode 2 has been announced officially, and even episode 3 and 4 are on the way. It's very cinematic, with probably the most intriguing storyline I've ever seen in a videogame. Over 20 hours of cutscenes in this one! Honestly, as time goes on, I'm less interested in playing the damn game and just seeing the cutscenes - that's a testament to this game's storyline. Being stuck for days on a boss battle hurts because you REALLY want to see more of the storyline evolve. <br>
<br>
Frequency and Amplitude - Amplitude and frequency are so similar that they may as well be mentioned in one breath. They're outstanding games! Definately worth checking out for any fan of music!<br>
<br>
SSX Tricky<br>
<br>
